- VSCode Version: 1.6.1
- OS Version: Microsoft Windows [Version 10.0.14953]

Steps to Reproduce:
- md foobar
- Create the following simple module (mod.js) - 

```
var exports = {};
exports.f = function (a, b) {
  return a + b;
};
module.exports = exports;
```
- 'Consume' the module (i.e. in main.js); open vscode with [code . in the foobar folder]

```
const m = require('./mod');
m. <- no intellisense at this point!
```

Note: jsconfig.json is present in the same directory with the following content - 

```
{
    "compilerOptions": {
        "target": "es6",
        "module": "commonjs"
    }
}
```

If I comment the assignment to module.exports, intellisense will re-appear. 

I would not use this pattern for exporting stuff, but unfortunately, there are libraries out there, using such pattern (for example adal-node (`npm install adal-node`)), for which intellisense does not work.

